b'Hi, I tried to submit this on my survey where it asked if any of the staff did anything memorable but was unable to because of the 1200 character or less stipulation. I really wanted you guys to know the whole story so you can understand where I'm coming from so here it goes..

As a stay at home mom, I don't get out much. I don't have many friends and I don't get to interact with adults very often. My days are spent caring for a six, four, and two year old. As much as I love being a mom, it's exhausting. All I look forward to every day is when my husband gets home from work so I can have a few minutes to myself or some time out of the house.  On Saturday, I actually got a little more than a few minutes. I wasn't by myself but I got to spend some one on one time with my six year old daughter. We enjoyed some shopping and decided to grab a bite to eat. She is a very picky eater, but she LOVES grilled cheese and I knew it was on your kids meal menu. So in we went to Red Robin in Hamilton Town Center. Our waitress was sweet, very friendly, and tended to us well. I can't complain about her service one bit. But this isn't about our waitress, this is about a special young lady named Dezzy. Dezzy came out with my second round of sweet potato fries and she was just simply amazing! I told her that my eyes had been bigger than my stomach because I was too full now that I had finished my burger to eat anymore fries, that I would probably burst if I ate anymore. She laughed and joked with me that she would wheel barrel me out if I needed her to. We laughed together and when she stopped she looked me in the eye and said, " You know, you're the only person who has talked to me today" gave me a hug and said thank you. As you can imagine, my heart just kinda warmed right up. So there I am hugging a stranger feeling a little emotional, thanking her as well. Because you see, nobody had taken the time to really talk to me either. Nobody ever does and that's why I appreciated that interaction with her so much more. I've never had a complete stranger hug me and thank me just for a little conversation, but I will tell you one thing, it sure felt wonderful. So thank you Dezzy for making this sheltered stay at home mom feel like a part of the world again and making me realize that I can make a big difference in someone's day, just like you did in mine. 
 

Red Robin people like Dezzy are special and I felt like you needed to know how lucky you are to have her as part of your team \xe2\x9d\xa4\xef\xb8\x8f'
b'Come taste the Love on Valentine\xe2\x80\x99s Day.'

b'Normally, I like Red Robin. I eat at your Columbia, MD store. Last night, we celebrated my nephew's Birthday at your Newnan, Georgia store. What a disappointment.

Several people's food came out cold. Refills of drinks and bottomless food never came. All around inattentive service. But the worst part was that I ordered something off the menu (I am vegan) that was literally purported to be vegan. "Order the veggie burger vegan and get it with bottomless broccoli." I asked for my veggie to come vegan. The first time it came with cheese on it and with fries. I sent it back and repeated that I wanted it vegan. The second time it came with mayo and fries again. At this point, I just told them not to bring anything but just to take it off the check. 

One of the other guests (another aunt) manages another restaurant in the area. She tried to talk to the manager to get this all addressed. Apparently, they took a slight amount off both checks. But the manager never came by our table. He didn't seem interested in making things right and there was no apology from him and barely one from our server.

Everyone else at the table ate their food while I sat in front of an empty place setting. How embarrassing and uncomfortable. I ended up going to Subway and getting a salad on our way home. 

I am disappointed and saddened by the treatment we received and by the lack of service and redress once we made the manager and the server aware of the issues.

Certainly, I will not go to the Newnan store again, and I will now need to think about whether or not to go to any of your other places if this is the level of service we can expect in the future.'

b'I developed extreme Celiac Disease after having 9 months of radical chemotherapy in 2011/2012.
If I eat at most fast food places I can end up in the ER. I was overjoyed when you opened a Red Robin near to me at the Palisades Mall, West Nyack, NY. I have eaten there (and at other Red Robins) on many occasions and only got sick once when I believe I was accidentally given a non gluten-free bun.
Your Company impressed me - took serious notice of my complaint and took steps to ensure that it would not happen again.
LOVE your burgers, the bottomless fries, your cocktails. Faithful Royalty Club member, but one question.
Why, oh WHY do you not have gluten free desserts? 
Mentioned that to one of your servers recently and he said "PLEASE ask the Company that - we get asked all the time".
Red Robin gets mentioned on my local gluten free FB Group regularly and has favorable commments on the "Find Me Gluten Free" mobile phone app.
You would be doing yourselves a BIG favor if you added gluten free desserts to your menu.'

b'Ordered delivery for the first time tonight to try it out and will NEVER do it again. Order was placed for delivery yet when we received the email it stated the order was for pickup even though it still charged a delivery fee. Email stated the food would be "ready for pick up" in 52 minutes from the time we placed the order. In an effort to find out what was going on we called the Gresham Oregon store over and over again and could not get through. The menu stated to click 1 to order or 3 to talk to someone. We clicked both several different times and all it did was route us back to the main menu. Since I wasn\'t home at the time I tried calling for 30 minutes and so did my husband. I finally got through and explained my frustration and he simply says "oh sorry about that". After checking with the delivery specialist he says that it is for delivery. At this time I tell him it\'s already been 20 minutes past the 52 minute window previously stated. He then says they are just running behind. I tell him I will have to come by to get the food since it\'s already been almost an hour and a half and we weren\'t sure if we now had to pick up the food. He said someone will be walking out the door to deliver in 5 minutes so I decided to drive back home. We are still awaiting the food and it has been 42 minutes past the 52 minute time frame give. Needless to say an hour and a half is not worth the wait for a burger.'

Below is a photo of the plate my entree was served on with a good portion of the corner chipped off. Manger had said she would not charge us for the appetizer. This was not done until we asked. \nThe dining room was not busy when we arrived. There were multiple empty tables, but by the time we left it was pretty full. Our meal took nearly 2 hrs from start to finish. We really enjoy Red Robin as a whole but normally visit a different location. b'\xe2\x80\x9cIf you could clone Colleen, the world would be a better place.\xe2\x80\x9d With the help of Dude. be nice we showed our love and appreciation for Colleen, one of our amazing servers from our Des Peres location. Warning: tissues needed!'

b'Dear Red Robin,

I'm writing hoping for help. Red Robin has always been a special part of our wedding anniversary celebration every year, for 25 years so far and we'll be celebrating number 26 in just a couple of days. We have a love that really began in a booth at Red Robin. I swear I can still see the rain on the window that night and smell the wonderful aroma that is Red Robin, and hear the staff singing happy happy birthday and suddenly, the group of us were all cracking up at something this guy across the booth from me said... and his blue eyes twinkled. Like actually twinkled! I know how it sounds, but they did!! That was it for me, I was in love! We were married 3 months later. Every year since then on December 16th (and many many times in between) we go to that location (Everett WA) and wait as long as we have to for "our" booth and eat and exchange gifts. On the very first year, I had ordered a taco salad, and as the server set it down, I could see a dime sitting there mixed in with the cheese. Before we left, my hubby asked if we could keep the dime. Later, I'd receive a framed dime with the Red Robin coaster as a gift (pic attached) and it's been on our wall since. 

Several years back, as a gift for my husband, I asked management there if I could have a very tiny plaque put at "our" booth if I had it made and got permission from management. After we told friends and family, a few of them have even asked to wait for that booth. Attached is a picture of it. Last year, however, we got a sad shock. The restaurant was being remodeled, and everything had been taken off the walls, including our tiny sign. The area that had our booth was blocked off and when I saw it was gone, I burst into tears. We never had a honeymoon, but we had Red Robin! The staff there was so very sweet, and opened up that area to just the two of us, but no one knew what had happened to our sign. As it turns out, I purchased 2 of them! (attached pics) I would like to get formal approval to place the second one in our booth. I know staff changes happen, and while a few people remember us, the people I got permission from have all changed. We would very much like to continue our tradition, and will be there again this year on friday, Dec 16th, for our 26th anniversary. Please allow us to place this teeny tiny plaque at our booth for the next 25 years, it would mean so much to us, you have no idea! My husband is my favorite thing in the world, and it would make him SO happy! Please?? \xf0\x9f\x98\x8a

Happy Holidays Red Robin!'

status_message:
b"OK... so last week I get a 50% GOURMET BURGER discount email sent to me.  I click on it and it's added to my rewards page.  I go to eat at the Nampa, ID restaurant and mention the reward.  The very nice waitress tells us to order and that it will appear when we go to leave.  We get ready to check out and she asks for my phone number.  I give it to her and she tells me the only discount coming up is a 10% discount off the order... She shows me the page... asks me for another number... we try my work number...no good... we go back to me regular number and the 10% discount is the only one showing up.  Not in the mood to argue,  I accept,  pay and go on my way.   This morning I checked to see where i screwed up.

No screwup on my part... as you can see in the attached image,  the reward is still sitting there... the account I took the screenshot from is the same (and only) one associated with phone number.  

I figure I got burned a couple bucks... not a big deal... just wanted to report where your new system broke down..."

b"What I ordered vs what I received. \nWhen the waitress brought it, I asked her if she was sure she brought the right thing because it looked nothing like the menu item. She picked it up, smelled it, and said it was right. I mentioned how there was no toasted marshmallows and she said they were out of marshmallows. Even with that, the Smores shake was supposed to have more chocolate and certainly no rainbow sprinkles. It was clearly the wrong item, but she insisted she could smell the graham cracker crumbs. Why on earth would they not mention that they were out of a key ingredient when a customer orders an item. I certainly didn't want something topped with sprinkles and whipped cream if I ordered something that was supposed to be topped with toasted marshmallows. I expressed my disappointment, didn't drink it, and she didn't remove it from my bill. What a disappointing experience."

b'If i could give this place negative stars i would. Was going here with my girlfriend every saturday for a while and had a great experience everytime til a few weeks ago. b'Here is a man who served our country for 19yrs. Risked his life for others. Comes to Red Robin often to get away and enjoy his evening, HERE is the problem. His wheelchair does not fit in the stall designated for wheelchair accessible. He cannot fit his hands where they need to go to lift himself onto the toilet, one hand balances on the wheel and one on the back of the toilet. This leads to countless times of not making it to the toilet in time to urinate in it. Then to top that off the soap dispenser is a push kind that cannot be reached... my bf who is an LPN happened to be using the restroom at the same time and helped him this time but also had this wonderful vet show him how he had to move around and struggle to use the bathroom.  Something needs to be done. Not just for this man but for everyone who is disabled and will have this same struggle.'

b"Just had a very frightening and dangerous experience at the Bellevue,  WA location.  My son is a Type 1 diabetic.  We asked to see the printed nutritional menu and he chose the prime rib dip sandwich,  note that it lists a carb count of 121g. We calculated an insulin corrected dose based on this information.  After his meal he felt Dizzy and nauseous when we checked  his blood count it was in the 30s! A quick Internet search and looking at what we found on Red Robin's nutritional app we found the actual carb count for his meal was only 69-76g.  That means he had taken almost twice the amount of corrective insulin for this meal.  This is totally unacceptable!  I returned immediately and spoke to the manager who though was nice,  understanding and compensated our meal in form of a gift card.  However these menus are a corporate responsibility and need to be corrected in all locations.  I'll be filing a complaint with @red robin gourmet burger Corporate and the local public health authority Monday."

b"A story about a man who went the extra mile for my little girl!
This past weekend we went to a Timber Rattler game in Appleton,on the way home all the girls wanted to have supper at the Red Robin. We had a great dinner and the service was awesome! However, when we arrived home (almost an hour away), Katie realized she had left her brand new, custom made softball headband on the table at Red Robin. This resulted in many tears from Katie. I was able to track down the phone number via FB of the Red Robin on Stoneybrook road in Appleton! The staff were so sorry and promised to look right away. I was feeling not a lot of promise that it would be found, or perhaps had been taken by someone else.
However, the manager called me back within 25 minutes to tell me that it had been found!!
The tricky part was getting it back to us. This amazing man actually offered to drive the headband to us, or meet me halfway. The guy lives in Howard, WI well over a hour or so away from me.
I explained that this just wouldn't work out with our schedules. So he offered to overnight the headband to Katie via FedEx. He felt that if it was that important to Katie, she would definitely need it before her next softball game. He had daughters and felt very empathetic towards Katie, realizing that athletes are often attached to certain things that bring them luck.
Today the package arrived!!
We are ever so thankful to Chuck Tietz at the Stoneybrook road Red Robin in Appleton, WI!!!
It does a moms heart good to see that many wonderful people still exist and are willing to go the extra mile to make a 9 year old girl smile again, and of course to make sure she's ready for her next game!!"

b"I wanted to write about my experience at red robin in Frederick MD last night. I decided to order the Black and Bleu burger wrapped in lettuce. It originally came with a bun and they had to take it back and wrap it in lettuce. That wasn't a big deal. But when I got it, it had barely any sauce, only a few mushrooms, no onions and no blue cheese crumbles. Translation....no flavor. I had already sent it back once so I did t want to say anything, but I did tell the waitress later. The manager came over and informed me that the burger only comes with he blue cheese sauce and mushrooms. I showed her the picture in the menu and description and said that it gives a false impression of what you get. She agreed and apologized. Let me say that my server Erin and the manager were extremely polite and accommodating and also, despite me protesting, took the burger off the bill. But I left very disappointed and unsatisfied with the meal itself. I have included pics of the menu. Either the menu needs to be changed, or the locations need to be informed on how the burgers are supposed to be made. Thank you for your attention to this."

b"I tagged your company in a post yesterday and decided I should share it here also.

It takes a lot for me to leave a negative review, so I hope that helps you to understand just how disappointed I was with my meal.
I went to one of your restaurants with my girlfriend and daughter to have dinner. She ordered one of the Gourmet Burgers and I decided to splurge and ordered the Black & Bleu from your 'Finest' menu. I did not place a complicated order, my only request being no sauce. When the burger arrived there were no blue cheese crumbles and there was lots of sauce. An irritating kitchen mistake, however, understandable, everyone makes a mistake every now and then. I informed my waiter, who apologized for the mistake. When my second burger arrived, the bun was barely toasted and there was nothing on it aside from onion and mushroom. The manager came over and asked if everything was ok and I informed him of the missing blue cheese crumbles, he promptly brought me out some. I took one look at the burger and wanted to send it back again, however, I was extremely hungry, and my girlfriend and daughter were already halfway through their meals, so I ate it.
I wouldn't even rate it as ok. The bun was toasted in a very small section and felt cool when I picked it up, the patty was warm at best, and the tiny serving of onions and mushrooms was greasy and cool.
Based on the menu picture, and I know the real thing will never look like a perfectly staged advertising photo, I was expecting an amazing burger and all I received was something that has turned me off Red Robin for a very long time, if not completely.
Here is a photo from your website next to a photo of my burger. I'll let you judge for yourselves."

b'I had the worst dining experience yesterday evening at your Hagerstown, MD location. First, we waited forever for our food. That alone wasn\'t awful (it was after all Friday night) but combined with the fact that when my food came it was incorrect it only added to my frustration. I had ordered my burger plain and it had come with all the fixings. The waitress noticed and whisked my burger away to get me another. (On a smaller note my son asked for apples and got fries but that was quickly corrected). My burger came back in record time which was impressive (although suspicious). I then noticed the bits of lettuce stuck in my burger. So I flipped it over to see mayo smeared all over the back. The cook who "replaced" my burger hadn\'t even bothered to wipe the mayo off. I was disgusted and lost my appetite at that point.  The management took my burger off the bill and then the night got even better with your new "toys" I went to pay. Overall it was just an awful experience which makes me sad because my family loves the food (and the gluten sensitive options) .'

b"After discovering a Red Robin was opening in Melbourne, Florida... I was elated. I regularly visited the chain in Kentucky and was excited to share the experience with my boyfriend, who had never been to the chain.

Today, Friday January 1st, we decided it was time to give the Melbourne, Florida location a try. We figured now that the location has been open for a few months that they would be running smooth. We were dead wrong. We recieved the text message saying we had approximately a 20 minute wait at 14:51 (2:51pm). We were seated at 15:16 (3:16pm). In the few minutes it took our waitress to arrive to our table we were ready to order.

2 burgers with fries. That's all. No appetizers, no food allergies, no special requests. 2 burgers with bottomless fries.

45 minutes later... NO food. Nothing. Our waitress never came back to give us an update. No manager coming by to check on us, although we sat with empty glasses for more than 15 minutes. Nothing. 

That is absolutely ridiculous. It's a damn burger!!! When there are empty tables in the restaurant there is absolutely no reason for it to take so long.

So, at 15:57 we left. We are done! We will never visit Red Robin again and you can be sure that we are making sure everyone we know, knows about our experience.

We went to Burger King across the street. Got 2 big ole' fat burgers for the price of 1 of yours... and we had it in less than five minutes.

I'm sorry we ever stepped foot inside your establishment. We wasted over an hour of our time today for nothing."

status_message:
b'This evening my husband and I decided to have dinner at your South Charlotte, NC restaurant (3415 Toringdon Way).  We have both eaten there before and had great experiences.  Tonight was not like our other visits.  Our waiter, whose name is John, never introduced himself to us.  I found out his name by looking at our receipt at the end of our visit.  John was very inattentive and came by to check on us one time in the 45 minutes we were there WITHOUT being waved over by my husband.  Not once did he ask how the food was or offer to refill our drinks.  He was very unpleasant and didn't seem interested in taking care of his customers.

I ordered the Avo-Cobb-O salad which was probably the only highlight for me during our meal.  However, I received less than 1/8 of a cup of dressing for the huge salad that was set in front of me and had to request more.  I had several mouthfuls of dry salad before John ever brought the extra dressing to me.  I had also ordered a side order of fries but did not receive those with my meal and the person who brought the food to us did not ask if everything looked ok and left before I could mention that I was without part of my order.  My husband had to wave John over to our table to even get him to notice that we had not received all of our food.  It was at least 5 minutes after we had received our food that I finally got my fries (and the extra ranch dressing for my salad).  When I did finally get my fries, my first thought was, "Seriously??  I can get more fries than this at McDonalds cheaper than what I am paying for them here."  (I am attaching a picture of the side order of fries I received.  In it you can see that I was only given approx. 8-10 fries.)  

I know that you have bottomless fries that you offer at your restaurants but 1) a side order of fries should include more than 8 fries and 2) our waiter would actually have to do his job for me to be able to take advantage of the bottomless fries.  My husband and I are severely disappointed in the lack of care and service we received tonight at the South Charlotte location of your restaurant and it may be a while before we visit after this experience.'

status_message: b"Nothing is worse than asking, no begging the girl to please make sure the burgers were well done. That being said about 20 minutes passed before they came out. I figured since all this time passed they had to be well done. One bite into mine and I'm greeted with a pink, COLD burger - FOUL. Was sent back and the girl did ask if I wanted another one. Who wants to sit there for another 20 minutes in front of their friend waiting like an idiot while they eat or while they tell you it's ok they will wait and their burger gets cold? What is even worse is they removed the one burger from the bill which was great but we only get further into the second one and it was still kicking and screaming. Totally ruined our night. McDonald's was across the street...they cook their burgers correctly but we stay from disgusting food. Now we can add your restaurant to the list!\nThe server was very nice and the manager offered desert. If they can't get a burger cooked right, why would I want them to bring us more food? All nice gestures but I really wanted the cook to be dragged out to the table and have them explain to me WHY! At 10 bucks a burger I would have expected to get it cooked. Everyone has their own preference of how they want their meat cooked and everyone will poke fun of others on if it's still kicking and screaming or totally dead. We wanted burgers that night and seen Red Robin and figured to try it out. Never again."

b"Great burgers, milk shakes, fries, etc. , but to add $1.99 for an entertainment fee is nuts. The ziosk is used to improve customer service, speed the process of ordering appitizers or pay the bill at the customers convenience. $1.99 isn't a big deal, most people have paid more for a cup of coffee. Please post this Letter to ALL their Facebook Pages!

To all Executives and Upper Management,
 Please know, this letter is to get a policy enacted, it is NOT AN ACCUSATION, as we are certain that the majority of restaurants support the Law Enforcement and Veteran communities. Unfortunately, in recent weeks, we have become aware of Employees and Management of many 'fast food' stores disrespecting Police Officers and Veterans in uniform by writing notes on food packaging and verbally refusing service to Police Officers and Veterans while on duty and in uniform. In addition, your attorneys should brief you on the Law Enforcement Officers Safety Act, which in effect, allows an on-duty officer to open carry in any place that it is not prohibited or restricted on government property. All your employees should be made aware of this law! As Americans, and Veterans, we stand with millions of Americans who see this behavior as unacceptable! We are requesting that all fast food and dine in chains send memos to all store Managers, Employees and Franchise Owners, and adopt a company policy of immediate dismissal of any Employee found to have committed this discrimination or harassment. Our goal, is only to get cooperation, but as we have seen, such incidents can lead to Boycotts and Nationwide outrage. We would like to think that the customers who support your business are ALL important to you. Those who put their lives on the line for our safety and freedom deserve respect from all who live under the veil of their bravery and sacrifice. We are requesting a response to let us know that you have addressed this issue, and that your employees have been informed of your policy, or change in policy...Thank you Sincerely for your cooperation in this matter.
 Your Customers"

b"Dear Red Robin,

I my myself have enjoyed the deliciousness your establishment in my hometown of Roseburg Oregon provides, even as recent as yesterday.  Fantastic experiences every time.

I wish I could state the same fantasticness in regards to how employees are treated.  (Take care of employees & they will take great care with your business.)

It has come to my attention that some of your supervisors & management at the Albany Oregon location are not up to speed on treating their women employees well.  It is 2015!  There is a nursing mother at that location that quite frankly is being treated like poop.  Besides the State AND Federal Laws protecting this woman's right to pump breast milk for her baby, WHO in this day and age wants to deny that awesome gift for a child or be so rude as to make a Mom feel like she shouldn't do the best thing for her baby.

I have to assume the inappropriate conduct by those supervisor members is NOT the entire Red Robin businesses stance on supporting Women, Moms and Babies.  PLEASE Educate ALL locations on this matter.  

Women deserve a safe work environment.  Women deserve to give the gift of breast milk for their babies.  Women deserve a SPACE and TIME at work to pump breast milk.  

Please support women and educate your establishments.  You never know when waves of women will come proudly dawning their breast pumps while enjoying delicious burgers.

Sincerely,
Showing Women Support
Robin N. Sproed

For your reading pleasure:
https://public.health.oregon.gov/HealthyPeopleFamilies/Babies/Breastfeeding/Pages/Laws.aspx"

b'Very disappointed with my local Red Robin in Eugene, Oregon: \nTonight my boyfriend Clayton and I decided to go to dinner at Red Robin after a long work week. We had just ordered our food and we were talking to eachother when my boyfriend looked over at the wall and noticed the two slugs on my side of the booth. We called our waitress over and told her we would be moving booths and showed her why. She said, "oh my gosh, that is gross! Uh....I\'ll be right back." She went to get the manager and he walked over to the booth and gave us a very dirty look, almost an accusing look of us bringing the slugs in! He was disgusted and walked away to get a to-go box and scooped them in there and said, "they didn\'t just get in here, they obviously were brought in." He never came over and apologized for our experience, he just walked away, nelecting to clean the booth further. Once we were served our food in the booth right next to it, another couple came in and sat at that exact booth, that still hadn\'t been cleaned. They ordered their food and asked if the manager was there, because they were friends with him. He walked out and sat in the booth with them for about 10 minutes, before we started to leave. After we paid, which we weren\'t "comped" for our bill, which we aren\'t worried about, my boyfriend proceeded to the booth to tell the couple that their friend, the manager, neglected to clean up where the slugs were. He then said, "there wasn\'t anything else to clean up," with a smug look on his face. No apology. Just continued to sit and talk to his friends on company time. Posted is the picture of the slugs in the booth. Sorry Red Robin, this manager has left us with a bad experience and we will not come back to this location.'

b'The Smokey Pepper Bacon Burger from your store in Lacey, WA. This was a "To Go Order". I called to let them know about my sandwich. They took the charge off of our order. But when I asked to get a free burger next time I'd like to come back, he said that they don't normally do that once reimbursed.  Mind you, all I ate was my salad, because the burger was "Mooing" at me. I ordered "No Pink". (I was still hungry and not about to go back to the store for a fresh burger at 10:15pm.)And the mgr argued with me. I don't complain about my food or service normally. This is the first time I've ever had issues there. However, all I asked for was a free burger for myself the next time I'd come in. And the Mgr acted like that was going overboard. I didn't expect a free meal. Just a free burger. If I expect a well-done burger, and I call at 9:45pm. You damn well know that I am not coming back into the store to get a new burger. 

He did reimburse my meal. I'm happy with that. He is going to send me a $10.00 gift card to replace the burger now via mail. But I shouldn't have had a MGR argue with me when I received a "Mooing Burger" served with a side of E-Coli inside of it. 

This doesn't mean I won't return back. We'll just go to the Olympia Restaurant from here on out. We've had exceptional service from them. 

Just keeping Corporate in the loop about the service given here is all. I don't expect anything out of this. Just hope they won't give another customer a hard time when they're served a side of Mooing E-Coli in the future. 

I also have a copy of the "Check Receipt".

b'Regarding your email to me offering a Free Appetizer.

I have a problem with the header of the email. It states:

"Thank you for your service"

 I am afraid you have the holidays mixed up, 

Memorial Day is a federal holiday in the United States for remembering the people who died while serving in the U.S.Armed Forces

Veterans Day is an official United States holiday that honors people who have served in the U.S. Armed Forces.

It also offends Veterans that businesses capitalize on a day of rememberance.'

b'Good morning. Thank you for the free appetizer for "my service", however, I don't want it. My husband is active duty and very much alive. Memorial Day isn't about thanking a soldier but thinking about a service member who has given the ultimate sacrifice and honoring them. I would appreciate it if you could resend this email to me around November 11 (Veteran's Day) 
Thank you again 

A wife of a soldier, not a widow'

b"So the family and I went to RR at the Renton Landing yesterday.  The food and service was mediocre, not bad but nothing special.  As I sat there talking and waiting for my food, I glanced up toward the Air conditioning vent (it was a bit cold) and noticed a crazy amount of dust.  I looked around more and all the railings and material on the ceiling was caked with dust, I mean this has easily got to me months and months worth. I even noticed a bunch on the light above our table, GROSS.  I mean how am I supposed to feel about what I am being served when the place looks like this?  We have always enjoyed going to Red Robin as a nice little family outing, but as we waited for the check we had a serious discussion as to whether we would return.  I just don't get the feeling that they really CARE, if they leave the restaraunt looking that way, scares me to think of what CARE is going into the food.  We have been LONG time (loyal) customers but after yesterday not sure. Something needs to be done."

b'I wanted to share that last night we had the WORST EVER experience in a Red Robin restaurant. :(  We planned to have dinner last night at the Kent east hill location (in WA) and the entire experience was awful.  

Arrived at 5:50pm and there were 2-3 parties stacked up in the lobby who hadn't been greeted yet.  My father went back and found a host (had been setting up a table for a party of 25).  We were seated ~6pm.  Our party consisted of 6 adults and one child celebrating her second birthday.

Waited at least 5 minutes for our server to take our drink order.  

Waited at least 10 minutes before our drinks arrived (diet cokes, club sodas and waters) and our dinner order was taken.  

At ~6:45pm we observed that the couple who had been in the lobby with us were leaving the restaurant, having eaten and paid before we even received food. At this point we asked our server how much longer our food would be and without checking with the kitchen she said, "it should be up soon."  

We ordered:

1) BLTA croissant (made correctly)
2) Chicken ensenada platter (the salad had no dressing and a knife was not provided to cut the chicken)
3) Southwest chicken salad (made INCORRECTLY - TWICE).  This was ordered with dressing on the side and both times it came with dressing on it.
4) Cobb salad (made correctly)
5) Lettuce wrapped monster burger (made INCORRECTLY on a bun)
6) Bacon cheddar burger on gluten free bun (made INCORRECTLY on a regular bun and had to wait at least 15 minutes for it to be remade).  This was my meal shared with my 2 year old daughter which meant that two of us had virtually nothing to eat while we waited for it to be remade.

My stepmom had finished her BLTA before the SW chicken salad and my burger arrived back at the table.  

We requested a manager who came out within a couple of minutes and while polite enough, STILL didn't ensure that our meal was delivered correctly.  

When the manager returned with some of the food (fry refills, but no salad or burger) he said he would take 50% off of each check (we were on 3 checks, meals 1&2, 3&4 and 5&6).  

The initial check arrived and it was for all 6 meals and 4 drinks, discounted 50%.  My father walked the check to the manager (in the expediting area of the kitchen) and asked him to please have it split.

The second round of checks arrived with the meals split correctly, the drinks split incorrectly and without any discount.  My father walked the checks BACK to the manager AGAIN in the kitchen. 

The third round of checks arrived with the meals split correctly and the discount applied.  Getting our corrected checks took AT LEAST 20 minutes.  

The whole experience from start to finish was absolutely wretched.  With a 5:50pm arrival time on a Wednesday evening at our neighborhood location (not a bigger location like Southcenter), I expected to be feeding my toddler by 6:30pm and it was WELL after 7pm before our food arrived.  

My husband and I both worked for Red Robin years ago (my first real job was as a hostess for the Pier 55 location) and I NEVER saw a customer have an experience this bad.  

I doubt we will ever return to that location, which is unfortunate because it's the most conveniently located.  

Also, I messaged this page and Katie responded that I should go to http://bit.ly/1Cl9xBN but it was not clear where to provide feedback.  Please feel free to email me at rebecca.munson@gmail.com.'

b'My family & I had the worst time last night at a restaurant that had become a sort of tradition for us. We all ordered our drinks, I got my diet soda but my sisters rootbeer float was no where to be seen. when he came back 10 mins later to take our food order, we asked for her drink again & the waiter apologized & said he thought he had seen someone grab it & assumed they had given it to us. He took our food order & said he would go check on her float. 15 minutes later 2/3 of us were brought our food, the 3rd person was told their order was still cooking, we again asked for the float & finally got it. We tried to wait until everyone had their food before eating, the server came back to refill out drinks & my brother in law asked about his food, The server said he was sorry but it was still cooking! My sister & I decided to start eating since our food was getting cold. I took a sip of my soda refill, Looked down into my glass & saw something frozen inside of my ice cube, I fished it out & found a little yellowed chunk. repulsed, I showed it to the waiter whom after examining it said "oh, that looks like just a seed". I stared at him & the seed until he admitted that it was "kinda gross" & offered to bring me another drink. b'More than anything in the world, please share this message to help our mission to make a difference in the world for the better: 

I've been extremely busy writing, editing, illustrating, self-publishing and promoting my series as well as taking care of our rescued parrots full-time.  Just 5 weeks ago, I was begged to rescue Chloe, a 5 year old Umbrella Cockatoo from Maluku, Indonesia who has been suffering from a potentially fatal condition called "prolapsing" in which the inner tissues of the cloaca protrude (hang out) from the vent, exposing the intestines.  It's treatable but she needs attention 24/7 to ensure that the herniated intestines don't dry out, thereby killing her or that she erupts them by attempting to push them back in herself.  She's responding very well to my hands on treatment in addition to increasing the humidity she gets exposed to several times daily.
	
I need your help to raise social awareness so that this problem, in addition to other self-destructive issues amongst endangered cockatoos and other parrots in captivity, stops.  Please share this cause that I set up amongst your friends and family:  Spread awareness about preventing self-destructive parrots  In addition, I set up a fund raiser for Pink Pearl's Parrot Rescue so that we can continue to help these poor animals: https://www.youcaring.com/manage-fundraiser.aspx?frid=261101 

Thank you for caring and paying it forward by sharing! Respectfully yours, Jes F\xc3\xbchrmann, author "The Diary of Pink Pearl, A Bird's Eye View\xe2\x80\x9d and "The Diary of Pink Pearl Continues: I'm Wide Awake and Born Again!" My  RIGHT OF DEFENSE AGAINST UNLAWFUL ARREST

Citizens may resist unlawful arrest to the point of taking an arresting
 officer's life if necessary.\xc3\xae Plummer v. State, 136 Ind. 306. This
 premise was upheld by the Supreme Court of the United States in the
 case: John Bad Elk v. U.S., 177 U.S. 529. The Court stated: \xc3\xacWhere the
 officer is killed in the course of the disorder which naturally
 accompanies an attempted arrest that is resisted, the law looks with
 very different eyes upon the transaction, when the officer had the right
 to make the arrest, from what it does if the officer had no right. What
 may be murder in the first case might be nothing more than manslaughter
 in the other, or the facts might show that no offense had been
 committed.\xc3\xae

An arrest made with a defective warrant, or one issued without
 affidavit, or one that fails to allege a crime is within jurisdiction,
 and one who is being arrested, may resist arrest and break away. lf the
 arresting officer is killed by one who is so resisting, the killing will
 be no more than an involuntary manslaughter.\xc3\xae Housh v. People, 75 111.
 491; reaffirmed and quoted in State v. Leach, 7 Conn. 452; State v.
 Gleason, 32 Kan. 245; Ballard v. State, 43 Ohio 349; State v Rousseau,
 241 P. 2d 447; State v. Spaulding, 34 Minn. 3621.

When a person, being without fault, is in a place where he has a right
 to be, is violently assaulted, he may, without retreating, repel by
 force, and if, in the reasonable exercise of his right of self defense,
 his assailant is killed, he is justified.\xc3\xae Runyan v. State, 57 Ind. 80;
 Miller v. State, 74 Ind. 1.

These principles apply as well to an officer attempting to make an
 arrest, who abuses his authority and transcends the bounds thereof by
 the use of unnecessary force and violence, as they do to a private
 individual who unlawfully uses such force and violence.\xc3\xae Jones v. State,
 26 Tex. App. I; Beaverts v. State, 4 Tex. App. 1 75; Skidmore v. State,
 43 Tex. 93, 903.

An illegal arrest is an assault and battery. The person so attempted to
 be restrained of his liberty has the same right to use force in
 defending himself as he would in repelling any other assault and
 battery.\xc3\xae (State v. Robinson, 145 ME. 77, 72 ATL. 260).

Each person has the right to resist an unlawful arrest. In such a case,
 the person attempting the arrest stands in the position of a wrongdoer
 and may be resisted by the use of force, as in self- defense.\xc3\xae (State v.
 Mobley, 240 N.C. 476, 83 S.E. 2d 100).

One may come to the aid of another being unlawfully arrested, just as
 he may where one is being assaulted, molested, raped or kidnapped. Thus
 it is not an offense to liberate one from the unlawful custody of an
 officer, even though he may have submitted to such custody, without
 resistance.\xc3\xae (Adams v. State, 121 Ga. 16, 48 S.E. 910).

Story affirmed the right of self-defense by persons held illegally. In
 his own writings, he had admitted that \xc3\xaba situation could arise in which
 the checks-and-balances principle ceased to work and the various
 branches of government concurred in a gross usurpation.\xc3\xad There would be
 no usual remedy by changing the law or passing an amendment to the
 Constitution, should the oppressed party be a minority. Story concluded,
 \xc3\xabIf there be any remedy at all ... it is a remedy never provided for by
 human institutions.\xc3\xad That was the \xc3\xabultimate right of all human beings in
 extreme cases to resist oppression, and to apply force against ruinous
 injustice.\xc3\xad\xc3\xae (From Mutiny on the Amistad by Howard Jones, Oxford
 University Press, 1987, an account of the reading of the decision in the
 case by Justice Joseph Story of the Supreme Court.

b"Red Robin would prefer not to service African Americans.  So since they can't tell African American not to enter the restaurant they hire one African American waitress and hope she is on duty to service the African Americans.  My family entered the Red Robin located in West Babylon, NY and was placed at a table and left there until their African American waitress came on duty.  While we were waiting we observed about 6 servers sitting around and the entire restaurant only had about 6 parties to serve.  The place was empty enough for one to get their food quick.  We were able to photograph some of the staff sitting around who could clearly see us sitting there.  When a white couple walked in about 5 minutes one of the servers gladly and quickly approached the couple and took their order.  We still sat there waiting.  It wasn't until their African American server came on duty that she came over to our table and asked us if were were being served because she noticed were had been sitting there for a while.  She said that wasn't her station but she would help us.  To make matters worse.  The MANAGER was circulating stopping by the tables asking the customers if everything was okay.  No once did he come to our table.  When the server told the Manager that we said we had been waiting for a while he told her to just serve us.  I guess he didn't want to be bothered.  What a disgraceful visit?  From what I hear, we were not the first Black couple who complained about not being served in the Red Robin Restaurant.  Your money is powerful.  You don't have to patronize an establishment that will disrespect you.  Take your money somewhere else.  If everyone does this Red Robin will be in the Black very quick.  Either with bankruptcy or lawsuits.  Either way, if you believe there is no place for this type of behavior in 2014 speak up by taking your business some place else."
b'My daughters thank you!'

b"I can't believe the service that we receive at this Red Robin Location.  I was saddened by the service this establishment provides.  The staff doesn't like to service African Americans.  My husband, daughter and I arrived at this Red Robin Location.  The hostess at the front provided us with a welcoming greeting.  We were then seated and that's when we witnessed the discrimination that the servers were exhibiting towards us.  We sat seated for approximately 15 minutes and no one came over to serve us.  The restaurant was pretty empty at the time because it was about 3:55pm when we were seated.  As we waited we photographed approx. 3 waiters standing in one corner, 3 sitting in a corner booth and one walking around.  Guess What?  The restaurant wasn't even busy.  It was half empty.  About 15 minutes a white couple was seated in a booth across from us and immediately one of the waiters standing around came over to serve them.  We still sat waiting. We continued to photograph the servers sitting around looking at us and no one coming over to service us.  The manager who was supposed to be greeting all of the customers never even came over to ask us how things were going.  It wasn't till an African American waitress came on duty that she noticed that we had been sitting there and not served.  She came over to help us.  The manager was well aware that we were sitting there because when the waitress walked away he walked up to her and told her to just continue to serve us.  We weren't even sitting at her station.  The waitress that was supposed to have our station was a white woman who the manager told our waitress that she was on break.  We continued to photograph what we were witnessing.  During our whole time in the restaurant the Manager never came over to our table yet he made sure he visited the other white parties that were seated after us.

Outraged is the only word that I can say.  This is the same situation that occurred with the Denny's restaurant and the African American Community was outraged.  That is why I continues to photograph what occurred so that I can submit the evidence of what happened at our first (and only) visit to Red Robin.  

I can't comment about the food because the situation that occurred left such a nasty taste in my mouth it was awful!"

b"I'm very disappointed with Red Robin tonight. 

Yesterday, we ordered a kids cheese burger for my son, made very clear his allergy to sesame and requested a sesame seed free bun. (We normally request the ciabatta bread, but our waitress assured us others were safe, so we got a wheat bun)

The bottom was COVERED in sesame, like cooked into the bun, there was also sesame seeds (3-4) on his cheese on top of his burger.

Luckily he didn't touch the burger at all, only ate fries, and we didn't even notice until we go the doggie bag in the car and my husband was going to try to offer him some.

I feel like this was a SUPER close call. We normally check his bun before he eats it, (like we did in the car) but since he as so uninterested in it in the restaurant we didn't while we were still seated.

I always have been told how great RR is with food allergies, but now I will think twice before going again.

I'm glad my sons birthday yesterday didn't end with a trip to the ER."

b'Greetings again.

A while back I shared with you a less than stellar experience I had in one of your restaurants and unfortunetley I need to do so again.

Let me point out something from the outset: earlier in life I worked close to 10 years in fast food; I started on the line and worked up to becoming a manager; I know things can get messed up, especially in the heat of a lunch or dinner rush & with a staff of young adults. That experience is why I dont go ballistic when errors happen; I have been there. However it is because of something else I have experience with that I feel I must bring situations like what follows to light.

I have a intolerance to gluten; it isnt one of those deadly allergies like a peanut or egg allergy (the paranoia I feel is bad enough, I cant imagine what those poor folks go through) but it can really screw with your day when triggered. My body hates gluten so much I dont risk eating something even just manufactured in a facility with wheat; just the dust will scramble my guts, and as such the rare event of going out to eat can be a nerve wracking experience for me.

Red Robin has always been an oasis in the sea of restaurants I avoid, a safe port in a storm.  But something seems to have been slipping for a little while now and my confidence is no longer as strong.

Last night, 6-15-14, we called & placed a to-go order at your Holyoke MA location; one of two locations in our area we visit. For myself I ordered my usual: Royal, protein style, with the GF fries (no seasoning). For my wife, her usual: Banzai Burger, also protein style (she doesnt have a gluten problem, she just likes it better that way) with turkey instead of a beef burger.

The place was quiet when I got there; everyone was their usual friendly self and I only had to wait a couple of minutes for the order to come out. When I brought the order home I gave the box marked Banzai to my wife and took the box marked Royal for myself.

While unwrapping her burger my wife was surprised to see a strip of bacon protruding from her burger - the Banzai burger does not come with bacon - and upon closer examination noticed an egg as well; we double checked the writing on the boxes; they were mislabeled.

I had not eaten any of the burger in my box, no harm was done, a quick switch of boxes and all was better...except, as I said above, in my confidence. 

When you are as paranoid as I have become your mind goes all over the place when things like this happen; like: what if two identical burgers had been ordered - something with lettuce, tomato, mayo & ketchup - but, because one person in a party had an egg allergy, one burger was ordered without mayo. When heated mayo turns clear; what If a person with a egg allergy got a mislabeled box.....?

I dont want anything, no one needs to call or write; I just want the confidence I had in RR to eventually be restored. I know you guys try and I dont have any answers how to make the issue go away; I just hope it does.

That is all I wanted to say.

Although, in closing, let me ask you this: Have you ever been to Disney World? My wife and I have been there better than 30 times now. People sometimes look at us like we each have two heads when they hear this but there is a reason other than it being a fun place for us: there is no better place to eat if you have a food allergy - period. We go there to relax and I truly can. If anyone in your office frequents WDW at all, have them make reservations at all the WDW restaurants they eat at on their next trip saying that they have a food allergy and ask them how it went when they come back. 

If you are interested in my experience there & have some time to kill, check out this blog post I wrote a number years back; its wordy but, I think, informative. We were there again in May and had a nice relaxing time:

http://kobolila.wordpress.com/2009/12/15/the-disney-gluten-free-dining-experience/


Have a MAGICAL Day!
'
link_name: b'The Disney Gluten Free Dining Experience'

b"I don't usually do this, but I wanted to post because of my disappointment with Red Robin tonight.  My family dines at our local Red Robin at least twice a month.  I am not so sure about anymore.  We arrived at 6:50 to a half empty restaurant (and a COMPLETELY empty bar section).  The host told me it was a 40 minutes wait because the kitchen was backed up.  We ended up waiting because we enjoy Red Robin.  We were seated in the empty bar area 35 minutes later.  As soon as we sat down, we put our order in (the waiter advised us to because of the kitchen).  We ordered at 7:20, and our food finally came out at 8:10.  The picture below is how my food came out.  50 minutes later I received my chicken sandwich with a breast that barely covered half the bun.  This tiny breast for $8.99?!  My fiance' received her chicken, and it was smaller than mine.  Unfortunately, this may be the last time we visit Red Robin.  Very upsetting for us."

b'Dear Red Robin: I recently ordered my meal with Freckled Fruit Salad instead of fries in an attempt to maybe eat a little healthier, but perhaps there has been a misunderstanding. This picture is what I was served (and not an isolated incident, as the exact same happened to my mom yesterday at a different location). It consisted of overly macerated possibly pre-frozen strawberries (the same that go in the Freckled Lemonade), apple chunks, and mandarin oranges (likely from a can) all floating in a sugary syrup. I believe this menu item is in desperate need of change, and should consist only of fresh seasonal fruit. Perhaps some varied melon chunks, red grapes, FRESH strawberries, blueberries, even blackberries would be good ideas depending on what is in season. But this muddled mess of sugary fruit is no good.'

b"I just wanted to say thank you for offering gluten free buns in your restaurants. My daughter was diagnosed with celica disease 2 years ago and hasn't been able to eat out at alot of restaurants because of the lack of a gluten menu not to mention kids gluten free menu. I had no problem paying an extra $1 so she could eat the same thing as her brother who currently doesn't have celica disease.  Our waiter was completely key in on everything and not once did I have to worry about her food being made. They even assured me the fries were even gluten free. Not only that our waiter kept informing us of certain things on the menu that were gluten free for future visit. When we got our receipt I notice there was a note informing the kitchen staff of her allergy. It was nice not to have to call a manager over to hassle them over my daughter meal to make sure everything was gluten free. Thank you."

b'My mom and dad were great R/R customers at the Des Moines restaurant visiting 2-3 times a week. They loved the staff and the staff loved them. My father passed away last July, but we kept the tradition alive with my mother. Pretty much, each Monday night, my boys, granddaughter, wife and I would meet my mother for dinner in Des Moines. The staff would greet us with huge smiles and hugs. They would stop to visit between customers and let my mom know how much she was loved. If we could we always sat in "Mom and Dad's" booth. March 25, Brenda and I met my mom, and a dear friend for dinner, sitting in "her booth". This was the last dinner my mom had and the last time I saw her alive. She was so happy, laughing and joking with us and the staff, although she missed John who went to manage the Kent, east hill location. With her tummy full, she marched out, got in her new car and drove home. She passed the next morning.
After a long day, we stopped by R/R Des Moines and gave the news to the staff, they were as shocked as we were. The next evening after running around and trying to get over the shock of my mom passing, we stopped in and had dinner, in her booth. Tina Bird was our waitress. She was so loving! She asked if it would be okay to get a plaque made and mounted at the booth dedicated to my parents. 
Monday, May13 after mom's internment, the whole family met at Des Moines R/R for a celebration dinner. My parents would have loved that!
The Plaque is up!
I want you to know, this staff has touched our lives bigger than just a restaurant. They are our friends. It is good just to sit and watch how they truly communicate and care about each customer and make their visit complete.    
Thank you for keeping Red Robin an experience and not just a restaurant!'

b"I want to share what I had just posted on my wall. :) Waxing poetic because I'm really hungry right now - for Red Robin, of course - even though I only went 4 days ago. (The picture is from that trip...)

\xe2\x99\xa5 Red Robin Gourmet Burgers: A Love Story. \xe2\x99\xa5

I first went to Red Robin when I was 3 weeks old. It was love at first sight, even though I couldn't eat solid foods yet. For every birthday I can remember, I've chosen to go to Red Robin. For most of my life I would refuse to even touch a cheeseburger anywhere else.

After we found out I had celiac disease, I was afraid to go to Red Robin again. I knew I could get my burger wrapped in lettuce, but it just wouldn't be the same. But the first time I went back, I was informed that Red Robin not only has gluten-free buns at most locations, but dedicated fryers as well. Their special seasoning salt is free of gluten, and so is their ketchup. I've never once gotten sick from Red Robin, but let's be honest: if I did, I would still go back.

Twice in my life I have had to deal with the horrible pain of seeing a Red Robin being replaced with an inferior restaurant. The last time this happened was just a little over a year ago. When I got that email I cried. Luckily, even despite this, I have never lived outside of a 15-mile radius of a Red Robin. I never plan to.

After almost every surgery, the first thing I crave is a Red Robin cheeseburger. No matter how nauseous I am, or how much I have been vomiting, a Red Robin cheeseburger pretty much ALWAYS sounds good. I think about them often. I have written poetry about them. I even dream about them. I could probably be a vegetarian, if Red Robin bacon avocado cheeseburgers weren't holding me back.

Market to the swing group through the eyes of the love group, my teacher always says. Well, as far as Red Robin goes, I AM the love group. I will be a customer for life. Their service and their burgers have no parallel as far as I am concerned. Their stories about various locations and employees' acts of kindness bring tears to my eyes. Whenever I eat a burger anywhere else, I feel a distinct, disturbing sense of disloyalty. Nothing else compares, and nothing ever will."
b'Flat Stanley visting Red Robin in Longmont, CO'

b"I have to share about how AWESOME my experience was at your restaurant today (Deptford Mall in New Jersey)!! To begin, my daughter has milk and egg allergies. I brought her food with me as I always do, because of cross contamination. Our waitress brought to my attention the care they take in dealing with Food Allergies and she was very knowledgeable. The manager came over to my table with a guideline binder containing foods that are safe. I can't brag enough about the staff and care that was considered in dealing with my situation. This was her first meal at a restaurant and to see her smile was priceless. This MADE my day and I hope that new chain location will remain open. Great service and extremely friendly!!!"

b"So.. I was contacted abruptly when I posted this on Red Robin's FB page and it was taken down pretty quickly. They messaged me and asked for the location and my phone number. I was contacted by the GM of the restaurant I went to and he apologized genuinely and asked for my address so he can send me some gift cards. I understand people make mistakes and said ok and gave my address. I received a letter from 'Lehigh Valley Restaurant Group' who apparently owns the Red Robin near us and was given two $10 complimentary gift cards to any of their 19 locations in PA. 

I kinda thought this was a slap in the face, not only did it barely cover what I paid for the individual meal, but gave me less than enough to purchase another. In restaurant guest relations, something like this should have resulted in, 'let me pay for this, and here is a coupon, gc, etc. to come back for one on us later'.

You want to keep my business, not lose my business."

b'Come on Red Robin... only the first 100 people get chili! 

FAIL....

I never even saw the email until 3pm! Did you really think you were going to have people running to Red Robin not even knowing if the offer still existed?

If someone was already going to Red Robin today and early enough they "may" have considered the chili offer a plus .... BUT they were already going to Red Robin so really you gained nothing. If you want to entice guests don't send us "maybe" offers!

Had the offer been 50% off chili all day I would have considered making a Red Robin run! The 50% would have covered your cost and just imagine that I may have brought a few guests and we might have ordered up some burgers and drinks.

You pay people good money to come up with ways to entice people to eat at Red Robin and yet it seems these very same people really don't think this stuff through carefully. This "Hell froze over" thing I am sure has cost Red Robin more that it gained you. I don't want to see more Red Robins go out of business!

Respectfully,
Gene'

b"Our closest Red Robin, Brannon Crossing in KY, is 40 minutes away but we aren't complaining!  Chad P. and Tanis, the two best food service managers we have ever met, are the reason we go to Red Robin often.  We literally trust them with our lives!

My daughter and I have severe Celiac disease & dairy allergies, eating out is not an easy thing for us.  We have been to MANY restaurants over the years that we walked out of, didn't feel safe enough to even eat.  Chad and Tanis are so caring, understanding and willing to do whatever they can to make us comfortable.  The steps they take go above and beyond, they make sure we are safe and happy EVERY time we visit. 

You seem to get more complaints and it's time you get some much deserved compliments.  You make life for people with food allergies/Celiac disease easier.  You give people the fun of a night out in a regular restaurant and don't make us feel like we're bothersome.  Your staff has ALWAYS been great, even while traveling to other locations.  Not all of them understood the precautions that Chad & Tanis take, but were always more than happy to accommodate us.  WE are so very thankful for Chad, Tanis and Red Robin!  Thank you  <3"

b'Why would you raise the price of the Cobb salad only to cut down the portion of the salad AND the triangle bread? We asked and were told the company changed the prep of the salad and to only give one small triangle bread instead of two. I think we will find a Cobb somewhere else.'

b'Super disappointed, Red Robin. Went to a Cincinnati location yesterday and two burgers were ordered at our table. Both were requested to be well done. Neither was well done. The minute the burgers were put on the table, the stench from them about made a couple of us sick. Neither of the burgers were eaten because they were so gross. The server (who by the way did a great job) explained that they have a new grill which replaced the previous cooking method and it is the "flame-broiled taste" that some people either really love or really hate.

Being a burger restaurant made famous for its burgers, that was a bold move to change something so drastic to your namesake food. They said it was a corporate move, not sure if that is true or not...but, I digress. It was not good. What a shame. :-( I have had better "flame-broiled" burgers from Burger King...and those aren't even that great. I, and the rest of the people at the table, wished you hadn't made that decision.

However, the French Onion soup was delicious! Glad you decided to bring it back. :-)'

b'I quite possibly just had the absolute worst customer service issues ever in the S. Plainfield, NJ location.  Waited 15 minutes for drinks, 50 minutes for 2 burgers and kids meals.  We watched the wait staff saunder around chit chatting with each other instead of taking care of business.  The only person doing their job was the bus boy!  When the food came a ridiculous amount of time later it was not even warm.   No exaggeration.  The food was room temperature and had obviously been sitting around for a long time.  

We returned everything except the kids meals (because they were starving and on the verge of tears) and asked to speak to a manager, who we were told couldn't talk to us at that time because she was busy cooking in the kitchen.  When she finally did show up, she apologized, informed us that they were having some "issues" and she was going to credit our bill for "most" of the food and come back with a coupon for a free appetizer for "next time".  15 minutes later, we received a bill for $24.00 (we indeed got charged for everything except our returned food), and she NEVER came back to give us that promised coupon.  When we left we saw her back in the kitchen cooking.  I guess her promises were just lip service.  

Sadly we watched at least 5 other parties with similar issues leave angry and unhappy for a variety of reasons.   This was a HUGE fail.   I am highly disappointed in Red Robin.  '
b"So, I just came back from lunch at Red Robin and didn't see the Santa Fe burger back on the menu yet.  When is RR planning on bringing it back?  :)"

b'The Puyallup, WA Red Robin is really going down hill.  We eat there a few times a month.  The last two times we have gotten orders to go and our burgers were awful and there were barely a handful of fries in the box.  We always ask for extra fries.  Now the fry sauce containers are half the size as well.  I had a mushroom swiss and there were about ten mushroom slices, the burger was black and there was wilted lettuce all stuck to the outside.  My sons burger was missing the onion straws.  Very disappointed.  '

b'Got back from dinner about an hour ago. Still hungry and finally decided to get on-line. Had 3 people in our party and went to Red Robin spur of the moment after much debating on where to go eat. Was the worst meal I ever had. Ordered the double tavern as did one other person in my party. Ordered them extra well cooked, even made a comment that I did not care if it was burnt. The other person was a child and had the kids burger and fries. Finally got our food and the other adult started eating the burger while I ate my fries, after a few bites I saw her spit out a bite and say look how pink this is. I cut my burger in half and could not believe how much pink was still in it. I would not have minded so much but we specifically ordered them extra well done. Finally caught the waitress and she said she would bring out new ones and she did apologize. In the meantime the child got to eat all her food as we still waited for ours. After at least ten minutes we got our new burgers delivered by the manager who very quickly said sorry, set the burgers down and ran. They were still just very slightly pink in the center. By then I had lost my appetite as that grosses me out. Tried to eat a few bites of the burger but just could not do it or enjoy it. The other adult ate about half of hers and thats all. Mean while the child was just sitting there, the waitress or the manager could have at least offered her a dish of ice cream or something since she was just sitting and waiting. What a waste of money and time, so disappointed. We like to do birthdays and such there and were very disappointed, it will be a long while before going back. Just felt like a number not a paying customer, hurry serve the food and fill the tables with another group of people, not fair.'

b"It's a sad time at Red Robin.  They have changed the meaning of bottomless fries.  It's only bottomless have you get a happy plate now, even for adults!  Sad times!  I like my fries BEFORE my food!"

b"I ordered the Avo-Cobb-O salad, with avocado being the featured ingredient. The salad arrives and there is no avocado on it! The waitress is busy with other tables and it is 20 mins later when she checks back in. By this time, we have all finished eating and I am very dissatisfied that I did not receive avocado on my salad as I was expecting. Instead of offering to take it off the bill, or even knocking a few bucks off since it was just a bare chicken salad at that point, she asks if I want a slice of avocado 'to go'. No, I do not want avocado at the point we are paying our check and walking out the door. We also had issues with the fries being undercooked (not crispy at all) and bathed in salt. When we mentioned this she only apologized and did nothing to make it right. Is your staff empowered to provide a positive guest experience at Red Robin? There are many other restaurant choices in Nashville and this franchise will no longer be one of those options."

b"To whom it may concern,\n        Today we went to red robin for lunch it was the worst experience I have had ever,  we go often the food and the service was always great! We ordered our food and asked for the burgers to be well done. We received our food after at least 20 mins. I cut my burger open and it was still very pink. I had to wait at least 5-10 min for someone to come near so we could ask them to make  me a new one,  she was so nice and said of course. This women was not our waitress that was supposed to be helping us.  I know stuff happens no big deal big kitchen etc. Then I went to the restroom with my daughter the manager I assume came over and let him know that she was going to make the burger how I wanted it and she wasn't going to charge us for it, really nice of her! Well they finally came with it again, cooked right but this time it had tomato and mayo I don't like that and had asked for it not to be on the burger the first time I ordered it. He said ok went back and finally made it right. At this point I didn't even wanna eat after waiting so long to finally get what I ordered how I wanted it. The waitress that was assigned to our section came over one time, we were there, we were there for an hour and a half and she came ONE time, after we flagged her down to ask her for the right jalapenos we ordered. She would help the people in the booth in front of us and the people who were sitting behind us, we were in the middle of them and she just walked by like we weren't there, I don't know if she was upset about the whole burger situation and didn't want to deal with us but that is not good customer service skills.  They attempted to charge us for two sides of jalapenos even though we didn't order the fried kind, we asked the manager of the kitchen to see if he could take it off they were still in the cup untouched, he said yeah but proceeded to tell me that he was going to have to charge us next time, I know this we pay every time no problem. We sat there with 2 napkins the whole time, she never came over asked if we needed anything or wanted more fries, we had to wait for the kitchen manager to bring my burger to me for the third time for us to even get refills on our drinks. Every time I come they always ask you and are coming by periodicity to see if you need anything else, when she gave us our check I put the phone number on it for the red robin royalty card  I looked and saw that we didn't get any credit for the stuff they did charge us for,  and when she came back and dropped the change off she was rude about it to, she just dropped it off and walked off, not a thank you or im sorry about anything, I never complain about anything but this was by far the worst service I have received. "

b'Oh Red Robin, you\'ve made me so sad today. I\'ve always loved you, but after today I may need to end our relationship. I ordered the usual--Bonzai Bruger; however, it was anything but usual. The meat was different. The pineapple was different. The bread was different. The sauce was different (maybe that it was a "sauce" and not a marinade). I think the lettuce was even different.  The manager and waitress were very nice nice explaining it and total corporate cheerleaders, but the truth remains that these changes did not improve on the taste or quality.  I understanding not offerring endless fries before the burgers come out; that\'s a wise business decision.  I even get no more balloons anywhere and the reusable kids cups; again, wise business decisions.  Changing your food? NOT a wise business decision.  It tasted like drive thru food.  I can\'t order it again. I don\'t know that I can eat here again.  And, for that, I am truely sad.'

b"Today my husband and I went for lunch at Red Robin in Eau Claire, WI because we had a free burger offer. We decided that we would try an appetizer, and placed our orders with the waitress and her trainee. After a while of talking we realized that our appetizer was taking a little long to show up, when a different waitress appeared with our burgers. She asked if we needed anything else and hubby mentioned that our appetizer had never come out. Just a couple of minutes later the restaurant's general manager came over with the appetizer and told us that it would be on him and apologized for the mix up. We thanked him, already pleased with the prompt solution to the problem. We lingered for a while, chatting about plans for the day. We were preparing to leave when the manager came back over, apologized yet again, and set a gift card on the table. He told us his name, shook our hands, then informed us that he had put $25 on the card and would love for us to come back to make it right! We were astonished, that level of commitment to a customer's satisfaction seems unheard of nowadays! Thank you, Chris and Red Robin for such a wonderful experience."

b'To whom it may concern, (customers included)-

My fianc\xc3\xa9 and I went to Red Robbin last night for a veggie burger dinner. We got our appetizer, and then waited for our food. Then we saw it. The food was placed in the heat lamp window, when the waitress finally noticed it, she looked upset. We were too. There was a chicken patty on one of our buns, complete with toppings. When the waitress alerted the cook, to say the least, he looked offended. They argued back and forth publicly and loudly, until he begrudgingly took the burger back, and ever-so-slyly replaced the chicken with the microwaved veggie patty, and promptly slammed it back up on the counter. (Sparking another shouting match.) at that time the other burger was finally ready 30 minutes after we ordered. (There were only 5 other tables in the whole place.)  reluctantly she took the plates  over to our table. I said ever so calmly, "excuse me, I just saw the cook take chicken off of my bread and replace it with the patty. That can make me sick for days, and is unexceptwble." She said "well, yeah, that did happen, but its okay." And started to leave the table. At that point it was personal. We raised our voices and said "excuse me!" And continued to tell her we wanted a new burger. She took the plate without saying another word. Then it got worse. My finances burger was still cold, the cheese was not melted, there were no toppings, and it was on the wrong bread. We looked for the waitress, but we didn't have to look hard. She was shouting back at the cook, in full public view with another woman who we later learned to be the manager. We then saw the manager smack the cook. That's when we had had enough. Unaware that the smacker was the manager we gathered our things and walked to the bar and asked to speak with a manager. The bartender was nice, and said 'of course' with out hesitation. He came back from talking to the girl who was yelling and hitting the cook, and said 'the manager will be just a minute.' At that point we decided to tell the bartender to pass along out troubles. We told him about our chicken veggie burgers that were "okay", our cold plain wrong bread burger, and the yelling, cussing, and smacking. We closed our argument by telling the bartender when the manager finally made time for us, to tell her that she should stop smacking employees in public view, and that we would not eat anything prepared by a cook throwing pans, and cursing customers because we would not eat a spit burger. 

My fianc\xc3\xa9 and I are both professional chefs of 10+ years. We have seen some duzies in our day but this was something else. We both have friends who work at different Red Robbins' across the country and are familiar with your corporate policies, most of which were violated that night. We will be waiting to hear how you are going to rectify this horrible, sickening experience. 

Thank you for your time. 

Stella and Lauren'

b'Just came back from the Settlers Ridge Red Robin, and had a strange experience.   My son LOVES RR and we go there often.  I don\'t usually order a drink, but to ring in the new year, decided to treat myself to an adult beverage.  Asked for the Baily\'s Shake, and was told the blender was broken.  On to plan B with the Electric Watermelon.  Well, I get halfway down the glass, and look to see a giant crack in the glass, and a few chips missing.  Of course I see this AFTER drinking half of it and any accompanying glass pieces.  We flagged down the manager who happened to be at the next table, and told him.  All he said was, "do you want another one?".   I was appalled.  I said no, and when we got our bill, I was charged not just for the drink with the broken glass pieces, but the Baily\'s Shake that we never received.  We told the manager, and he finally took the drinks off of the bill.  Pretty little compensation to have to ask them not to charge me for a drink I never received, and one that could have possibly injured me.  The waitress, while very attentive throughout the meal, never mentioned, it once.  Either she wasn\'t informed by the manager, or just didn\'t care. Either way, we were very saddened by such lack of concern or empathy for the situation.  Had it been my job as manager, I certainly would have not merely offered up a "refill" but taken care of things in a much more positive manner.'
