b"Sorry to say we ate at our local Red Robin in Grand Junction, CO tonight, and again we had a horrible experience. It really seems every other time we go we have MAJOR problems. Tonight was no different. We got there about 4:45. The restaurant was not even half full. I did hear as we were waiting to seat that they were down a server or two. It should have been my first notion to leave. (We have encountered this issue several times). We were seated pretty quickly tho. Our waitress was initial very nice, but that was the end of the good service. We ordered our food with out initial drink order. Almost twenty minutes later ( we had not seen the server in that time) we began to get frustrated. Our glasses were dirty, they looked like someone licked them around the rim. When we asked where our waitress was, no one knew who it was. After describing her, turns out the bartender was out waitress. (Would have been fine if we were eating near the bar) Finally the food arrived, of the 5 meals we ordered 3 had to go back because they were wrong/ or ice cold. After we had to send a soup back a second time we gave up. When speaking to the manager instead of an apology we were told we we luck to sit as quickly as we had because they were low on servers, and had the bartender not waited on us we would have had to wait longer. Never did we get an I'm sorry from the manager, only that the food being wrong or cold was not the servers fault. It the restaurant had been slammed I would have understood a little more but, seriously over half the tables were empty. The lack of caring from the management was the worst part of the whole thing.I am really wondering why I keep giving this restaurant a chance...... "

b'Extremely disappointed with the poor customer service and decreased standards of Red Robin. I used to be a hostess and then a server at Red Robin.  At that time quality was mandatory and the strict policies that produced an exceptional customer experience were ingrained into us. 

Based on my prior experiences I was surprised to receive horrible service at a Red Robin location. It was so bad and I was so shock that I felt compelled to fill out a comment card. Comment cards are no longer available. Instead I had to go online with an access code to inform corporate Red Robin of my horrible experience. The form specifically asked if I wanted to be contacted and I did. After submitting the form, I received an auto generated email letting me know they will contact me in 2 days but if they don\xe2\x80\x99t here is how to contact them\xe2\x80\xa6 AGAIN. 

Are you kidding me? Where is the service in that? This company is dropping the ball yet again with a person who is already upset about poor service. The message was clear and contradictive, I was told a timeframe for callback then in the next sentence they infer that they frequently don\xe2\x80\x99t make the contact and it maybe my job to hold them accountable? Well no big surprise I did not get that follow-up call and at this point it is clear to me that Red Robin has no intentions of improving service. Very sad, this used to be a great restaurant.
'

b'Buffalo Wild Wings in Murrieta refused to serve my family yesterday. As many know my daughter has life threatening food allergies. Prior to eating anywhere we check online to see if they have anything she could have.I had checked and they could not guarantee no cross contamination. We picked up some safe food for her....she would order a drink from the place and the rest of us would order our meal. We do this every other place...Chili's, Roadhouse, Red Robin. We have done this for over 15 years! The waitress came over first and said "you cannot bring your own food in" I said "She has food allergies so we can." 
We were in the center of a crowded room. 
The manager came over and told us we had to leave we cannot have her food here-Loud so everyone could hear. Jessica began to go get her crutches and the other kids got up to help. I again said "she has food allergies, we are ordering food but she cannot" ...Its terrible what happened next...and no matter how hard I explained she came back with ignorant remarks.
We have known allergy laws for over 18 years now. We are educated on health and safety codes and FDA rules....we were just trying to eat together as a family. The lady had the nerves to then say "I had to kick out a group on Monday who came in with their own food and ordered water to watch the game" as if our case was similar. Asked for a general manager...he wouldn't be in till Monday. Asked for cooperate phone number-she does not have it. 
Needless to say we are asking everyone to boycott Buffalo Wild Wings until they hop on board with working with families who have life threatening food allergies.'

b"This was a very hard week.  I am a middle school teacher and on Wed. morning one of our teachers was hit by a car while jogging to work.  He died of his injuries.  The teachers and students at my school have been grieving since Wed. morning.  We all needed a weekend and were excited for school to end on Friday.  

When I got home from work my family decided to go to Red Robin for dinner, we went to the West Valley, UT location.  I still had on my faculty shirt and after we were seated the manager, Nic Turc, after seeing what shirt I had on, asked me what my connection was with that school.  He proceeded to offer his condolences and the condolences of the Red Robin family for our loss.  It was very touching to see how my pain became his pain.  A few minutes later, after ordering our burgers, Nic returned with two orders of onion rings and mozzarella sticks on the house.

We choose to go to the Red Robin in West Valley even though there is another location closer to us because of the amazing customer service and food quality there.  Even though a few free appetizers won't bring back my friend, Nic was able to ease the pain so we could enjoy a nice family dinner.  Thank you Nic Turc and Red Robin, you have made a customer for life!"

b'Red Robin Rocks!! I was a first time customer today at the store in Orchard Park, NY. I was completely taken in by the menu presentation, the decor of the store, the great food but more importantly your superior wait staff. I have been in the hospitality industry for over 20 years and it takes a lot to impress me. Your waitress Amanda did just that! My son and I were at Dent Neurological earlier and decided to visit Red Robin. I have seen the commercials and never understood them, so I was curious. My son has orders to eat more red meat and has been a visitor to another store and really enjoyed his food. Upon entering the store, we were immediately greeted with the most genuine hello and smile. The hello and smile immediately put me at ease and made me feel welcomed not a problem or just another tip. I requested a warm area due to being chilled with the drastic change in New York weather. As we walking to a table, Amanda took her time and stood at different locations. At first I was confused, but then she announced to me that this spot should be suitable because she could feel the heat. She was right,I was pleasantly warm the entire time. As we sat down, she handed us our menus and begin to "suggest"items. The difference here, Amanda asked probing questions and really listened and was able to figure out what I liked. I must say the gingerbread shake was to die for and completely hit the spot and started off our dining experience on a wonderful positive note. As Amanda explained the menu, she was very honest and very knowledgeable. I never felt rushed and never felt stupid or that I was taking up too much of her time. More importantly to me, she never said a word about my son or the fact that he had his hood up.(His head was wrapped in gauze due to some testing) Amanda treated us both like we were long time customers or even regulars. She smiled all the time, had a joy in her voice, and a very pleasing way about her. I overheard her talking to other customers and it seemed as though she would go out of her way to help any of her customers. She treated everyone as though they were long time customers of the store. Amanda took ownership of her presentation and her personality. It has been  a long time since I have had the pleasure of a wonderful server. Combine great food and wonderful wait staff and that store could do no wrong. I will definitely be back more and have already recommended that particular store to many. Please take the time to let Amanda know what great service she provided today. Thank you Amanda for making our day enjoyable!'

b'So, I work at the Spokane Valley Red Robin in Washington. Today this man came in telling us that six years ago he asked a woman to be his girlfriend in our Red Robin, at a specific table. b'A HUGE shout out to our West Hartford Team! We received an awesome letter from one of our Guests, and we couldn't resist sharing a bit of it here\xe2\x80\xa6

\xe2\x80\x9cTwo years ago my youngest daughter, Reagan, was diagnosed with Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML). She was only 15-months-old at the time. After five rounds of intense chemotherapy during an almost seven month long hospital stay, our baby girl was finally allowed to come home in May 2011. Reagan is still in remission and was recently granted a well deserves Make-A-Wish (MAW) vacation. The MAW volunteers notified our family that prior to our trip to Disney World, we would also be treated to a dinner at the restaurant of Reagan's choosing. Naturally, she advised Make-A-Wish that she wanted Red Robin. Here's where the story gets REALLY good...

We arrived at Red Robin and discovered that our table had been decorated BEYOND expectation. The staff bought Disney Princesses placemats, plastic cups, coloring books and crayons, mini-dolls and more pink & purple balloons than you could count. The Managers thanked US for being their guests and for allowing them to serve our family. My wife asked our friends from MAW if this was the reaction they received at other restaurants, and the response was essentially "No, this is above and beyond what we normally see." The topper on the night was when one of the managers came to our table and told us that dinner was on Red Robin. I think our MAW friends' jaws hit the table at that one. Apparently, this too is not the norm for such dinners.

I wanted to let you know what a great community organization Red Robin proved itself to be tonight, as well as give a great big THANK YOU to the team at your West Hartford location for making my Reagan's night so special. You should be proud to have such amazing and caring people working for you. My family has always been good Red Robin customers; however, as of tonight we are truly Loyal Customers and will be telling everyone and anyone who will listen about our wonderful experience. THANK YOU VERY MUCH!!!!\xe2\x80\x9d

Bill K
West Hartford, CT'

This red robin has been the only restaurant we've had successful trips to.  A big thank you goes out to the special menu binder we get to look at to accommodate for his allergies. Red Robin, thank you for making our lives better! It's so nice to have a safe place for us to dine when we don't feel like cooking!"

b"I want to extend thanks to the Beaverton, OR location for amazing service this past weekend.  It was my son's birthday, and he has autism.  Red Robin is his favorite restaurant, and a birthday tradition.  We arrived for lunch and had a short wait (10 min.). This was almost too much for him, as his birthday already causes overstimulation. Fortunately, your manager Ashley, recognized the situation and made sure that he had fries on the table the moment we were seated.  I know this isn't typical, and I really appreciated the accommodation to make our meal more enjoyable.  One of our other sons requested fruit punch off of the kids' menu, and apparently they no longer carry it.  Our server, Travis, created a concoction of sprite, grenadine, and some sort of orange / raspberry syrup combo that ended up being a perfect beverage for him.  To top it off, our birthday boy is dairy-free, and I had accidentally left his special ice cream at home.  Your staff provided a dairy-free smoothie for him during his birthday song, and we had over half a dozen employees singing to him, even though the restaurant was quite full. Thank you for making our experience extra-special.  Your staff went above and beyond! Thank you more than words!!"
b'Light the Night Event for leukemia and lymphoma society'

b'After waiting for many months for your new Brandon, FL location to open, we decided to have dinner there tonight. When we walked up, there was a line outside and a girl putting names on the list on an iPad. It was going to be 45 minutes for a table for myself, my wife and our two young children.  We understood that it was Saturday night and that the restaurant has just recently opened, so we were good with waiting the 45 mins or so. We put our name on the list and were going to receive a text when our table was ready. Name went on the list at 5:59. We went and let the kids play in the play area at the mall and commented how wonderful the text deal was so that we didn't have to wait right at the restaurant. At 6:50 I went back to the restaurant and went inside where I stood around for 5 minutes waiting for one of the hostesses/greeters/whatever to speak to me. I realized as I was standing there that 3 other customers were aggravated that their tables were not ready in anywhere near the promised time frame. One of them talking to what I assumed was some type of manager. Eventually when I was spoken to I was told my table would probably be another 30 minutes. We ended up eating garbage food at the mall food court because there was no way our kids were going to hold out another 30 mins (nor is a "gourmet hamburger" worth an 1h15m wait just to be seated).  

I get that, as a company, you all have to optimize seating and the queue and that you all have obviously purchased some software that is supposed to do that for you. The text thing is cool, however the software obviously isn't working well.  Sometimes fancy gadgetry can't replace the good old human brain and some paper and pen. 

On top of the software issue it appeared it was mass mayhem in there amongst the employees. The 4 or 5 greeters/hostesses seemed to be tripping over each other, panicked and didn't seem to have any real sense of direction from management as to who was doing what. I actually felt bad for one of the girls, she just looked disappointed that she'd accepted this new job. 

Bottom line- get the software working right or go back to pen and paper and make sure management is actually "leading" the team and not just calling himself a "manager".

We'll wait a while and let the newness calm down before we give it another go..........
'
b'When is the gingerbread shake returning?  You all should just keep that year-round.'

b'I am a team member at Red Robin in Lincolnshire, IL.  We always share team member UBAs (Unbridled acts) but last night I witnessed multiple guest UBAs that I wanted to share.  

I was waiting on 2 members of our armed forces who were in uniform.  A random guest approached our host and asked to see the server waiting on these two men.  When I arrived, she asked me for their bill and paid their tab.  She wanted it to be anonymous and to have me thank them for their service.  What a great message to deliver to the table!

A few minutes later, a fellow server told me that her table wanted to buy my table dinner.  I explained that the tab was already picked up by another guest.  Her table offered to buy dessert to thank them for their service.  

These two members of our military were greatly appreciative of the random acts of kindness.  As a server, I was so moved by the generosity of the guests at Lincolnshire RedRobin.  As we approach the holiday season, my hopes are for more random acts of kindness to all.  

Thanks for letting me share :-)'

b'Well let me start of by saying that I did not have a wonderful visit on October 4th 2012 at your Masonic and Gratiot location in Michigan! I took my 3 children and myself out to dinner for our birthdays. Yes all 4 of us in October and my children chose to go to Red Robin because they like it when you sing Happy Birthday to people. It was a Thursday night at not that busy but to my surprise.....We waited a long time to receive our order. In the meantime our waitress got three more tables at once that I know of. She became busy very quickly. We needed refills on drinks but knowing that she got really busy at once I waited patiently. I am a server as well and know how quickly a situation can become hectic fast. About 5 minuted into eating our dinner my daughter then had to use the restroom. So all four of us got up to use the restroom leaving all our coats. We come back to our table to find that all of our FOOD HAD BEEN CLEARED OFF THE TABLE AS IF WE LEFT! The busboy was behind us and apologized very quickly realizing that we did not leave. Our waitress appears and my daughter is now crying  and saying where is her hot dog! The waitress offers to make it all again but I decline. I did not want to wait another 20 minutes to get  our food but asked her to please come and sing happy birthday to the kids being it was the whole reason we came there in the first place. She apologized again and said she would be out to sing right away. As I am waiting at the table a manager then proceeds to come to that table to talk to me about replacing my meal. Didn\'t I just say that I didn\'t want to wait anymore that clearly this is not a good night for me to come here. He then offers for me to take a carryout. If I wanted to order a carryout. I would have. I don\'t want to take home food and save it for later. I\'m not a left over type. It just doesn\'t taste the same. He then says if I change my mind I can take home meals. In the mean time still no Happy Birthday! Why am I waiting so long for my kids to get a simple Happy Birthday! I would have already left. They finally come out to sing happy birthday and the waitress apologizes again. Now here is my biggest shocker! Do you know that I received the bill and NOTHING...I MEAN NOTHING WAS COMPENSATED! I was so pissed that I actually thought about just leaving a note that said "how can you expect someone to pay for food they did not eat????" However I did not.  I politely payed my bill and left a 20% tip as well. Never the less. I payed for all my food that was cleared from my table and we barely got to eat. So i guess because I didn\'t want a carryout....that meant I will pay for all the food I did not eat! I will not return to this location!'

b"Listen here. Today, (or yesterday since it's 12 o'clock) was my parent's wedding anniversay. My family and I went shopping earlier that day, so we were pretty tired. And my mom and I hadn't ate very much earlier that day because we were busy. And since it was their wedding anniversary, we wanted to go some place nice. So we decided to go to the district of tustin's red robin. (Since the other one closer to us shut down). Well, my dad put in his name and how many people we had (which was only 4) and we waited. And waited. And waited. Then some lady called someone else's name and party of whatever. Then another. Then another. We waited around 30 minutes. Yes, it was a busy night for red robin's, but that's no excuse. Because while we were waiting outside, a couple of two put down their name and five minutes later, they got a table. Then a group of five people came, put down their name and ten minutes later, they got a table. It wasn't until my mom complained to those ladies, that we got a table. So everything's all dandy now that we got a table, right? Wrong. Some nice lady, took our drink orders and went away. But then some other lady, who was obviously a newbie, wanted to get our drink order. We already ordered drinks. So instead she took our food orders. The same nice lady came and gave us our drinks. Then five minutes later, the same nice lady brought us fries. Now, I know that doesn't seem much, right? But by then, we were STARVING. That little act of good customer service, THAT'S what you guys need to learn from her. She turned our bad moods into good ones. Because before her, we recieved AWFUL attention. One of the worst, if not, the worst customer attention ever. Later that night, we found her name. Serena. Serena of the district of tustin's red robin. Remeber that name. She changed our dining mood that night. With those two baskets of fries. It's small details like that, that you guys need to work on. We've been to the market place's red robin all the time, before it closed down, because we got good customer service, and reasonably priced food. But you need to shape up, red robin. Or else you're going to lose customers for bad customer service. Because isn't it about the customer who orders your food, and pays hard earned money, to expect good service in return? Without Serena, we would've never come to any red robin's ever again. But because of her, in the future, we probably will come again. So the moral of this whole story: train your employees better in good customer service, or else they won't come back at all."

b'The Red Robin in Brighton, MI is wonderful!  I am a volunteer with the Make-A-Wish Foundation of MI.  My partner and I brought our wish kid and his family to that particular restaurant.  When we arrived the manager pulled me aside to ask me what our wish boy was interested in.  A while later as we were eating our meal (Generously donated by Red Robin!) the employees surrounded our table and presented our wish boy with a huge gift bag full of Star Wars toys! Later, when everyone at our table had exhausted our supply of quarters because our wish boy loved playing the crane game, each employee reached into their pockets and donated any quarters they had.  Such loving generosity from these young people! We found out later that each employee had pitched in to buy our wish boy his Star Wars toys.'

b"A friend 's kid lost his wallet last weekend with $300 he had been saving for 2 years. When they realized he had lost it, they contacted the places they had been. The Red Robin at 6795 S Cornerstar Way Aurora, CO 80016/Parker and Arapahoe, called them and let them know his wallet had been found. They returned to store to get wallet and money was gone, a tough lesson to learn... They left the store, mom and son in tears. The manager, Parker, contacted them the next day and invited them to come back for dinner as they felt horrible this had occurred. The family went back to Red Robin at 6795 S Cornerstar Way Aurora, CO 80016/Parker and Arapahoe, The store's employees had pooled their money together and replaced what was lost. You don't hear enough about the good people do in this world and I believe this story needs to be shared. So, if you are in the mood for a good burger and want good people to serve you then give Red Robin at 6795 S Cornerstar Way Aurora, CO 80016/Parker and Arapahoe, your business. What a good team!  this was posted by a friend of mine in Colorado....Just wanted Red Robin to know what great people they have there!"

b"OK so I just redeemed my $5 coupon at the Liberty, MO Red Robin for a couple of burgers and a salad, to go.  I ordered at the bar as I was directed to do and then sat at the bar waiting for my order, and sat, and sat.  All while watching bags of take out being delivered to the bar and watching them being given to other patrons, most of whom apparently had ordered ahead and just came in and picked up the food.

Except for this one bag that the bar tender kept looking in every time a new bag would be set on the bar window for take out.  She kept looking in this one bag in this one bag and either returning it to the window or shuffling it off to the back counter and moving it from one spot on the counter to another.

Finally, after about 20 minutes of this mystery takeout bag being shuffled about all the while cooling off, the bartender decides that is was my order.  I thought it was for some one that had call ahead but hadn't arrived yet to pick up the food.

When I brought it to the bartener's attention that it had been sitting there for at least 20 minutes, she offer no explanation and no apology.  If I hadn't been so hungry by that time I would have asked for the food to be remade.  I took the food and it was room temperature by the time I got it home.

Needless to say, I may eat at another Red Robin in the future (not one of my regular spots) but if I do, it will not be the one in Liberty, MO."

status_message: b"Ate lunch at a Red Robin in Easton, Pa. today (since we were traveling through Pa.), and service was rather poor. We went there about 12:30, think that they would be busy, but wasn't, and now I know why.  We were seated right away, waited 10 min before the waiteress aknowledged us, Other customers in her section that were seated after us she aknowledged right away) she took our drink order and asked if we were ready to order, we told her to give us a few min.  when she returned with the drinks, we gave her our order, We waited 25 min for our meals, everything was correct but the burger was cold, I told her the burger was cold and she took it back to the kitchen, she was gone about 2 min later with a hot burger, all they did was throw it in the Microwave, There is nothing worse then wilted lettuce, hot Tomatoes and soggy onion straws. Manager made the mistake of stopping by and asking how things were. I told him exactly what was not right.  He was very apologitic and asked what he can do to fix it.  He offered a new burger, but then why would I wait to eat as my family ate there food?  (why is it that the mgrs ask What they can do to make it better?)  shouldn't they come with a solution to the problem?  The Manager covered the Tab and then apologized for the service again, The manager did his job. This is not the first time that we have had issues with service at a Red Robin.  But we still keep going back."

b'A server team member is expected to receive no less than 3 guest voice (online survey) responses per month. A guest voice survey asks a plethora of questions, but in the end, asks the guest to rate their experience on a scale of 1-5. 1 being poor, 5 being excellent. If a server receives a 4 (4 equals good) the survey is graded as a zero and the server receives no credit for doing a satisfactory job. \nShould a server, regardless of how many shifts they are given a month, fail to receive at least 3 responses, they are sat down and reprimanded for poor performance. If the problem persists, shifts are taken away. '

b'A HUGE shout out to our Team Members!
 
Recently Mo, one of our regional operations directors, reached out about a fellow Team Member, Wendy, in need. Wendy works at our restaurant in Augusta, Maine, and is a single mom of two kids, 10-year-old Maddy and her sister Sophie, a child with autism. While at work, Wendy received the dreaded call that Maddy had a seizure and was being rushed to the hospital. Upon arrival the doctors found a brain tumor, requiring immediate surgery and subsequent chemotherapy and rehab sessions.
 
The cry of support was for post cards around the world to add to Maddy\xe2\x80\x99s collection. However, what the family received was so much more! An \xe2\x80\x9cUnbridled Act\xe2\x80\x9d in its truest form.
 
Many restaurants in the New England area and beyond donated tips, wore Maddy\xe2\x80\x99s favorite color orange, and sent in photos, gifts and notes of encouragement. In just two weeks, over 100 postcards stretching from across the U.S. and European coast were received and a generous amount was raised by our Restaurant and Home Office Teams to help with the medical expenses!
 
\xe2\x80\x9cWhen an entire company, its franchise partners, vendors and family of TMs come together to support a little girl they have never met in the middle of nowhere in Maine that is LEGENDARY!\xe2\x80\x9d ~ Mo'

status_message: b"All I have to say right now is I am overwhelmed by the only Red Robin in Durham, NC ( New Hope Shopping Center). I have always had great experiences at RR, but on my son's birthday there was a simple mistake with their not singing to my son, but then coming out to sing to another table. Since then, RR, and their general manager Tyler has gone above and beyond anything I expected. Actually, I didn't expect anything -- I just wanted to bring this matter to their attention. He is bringing my son back in this Friday to celebrate his birthday again and feeding my family. My son is so happy. Since he has special needs, he does have depression and gets bullied. When ANYONE reaches out to do something kind for him, it means a lot. I know I would not experience this outstanding level of customer service from 95% of the resturaunt industry.  Thank you, Tyler and Red Robin for your service and stunning me with how you deal with things in your business. I can't wait to let you know our experience on Friday. Thank you! <3"

b'Something very sad happened at Red Robin the other day. I felt almost discrimated against because we had a small table. Anyhow, we are not a rich family, but when we do go out, we always tip well and all that. I have been a server, so I know how it is. Anyhow, my son was turning 11. He has special needs( autism), and every year on his birthday he gets to choose a place to go to. He chose Red Robin. As said before -- we are not rich, and this is something we had to save up to do for him. Our server walked up to our table and said they did not have time to sing happy birthday to my son, but I SWEAR, within 2 minutes they came out singing to a LARGE table full of adults. My son cried. Thanks Red Robin!'

b'WOW!!! We had an amazing evening at the Plainfield Red Robin! Since we had a large group, we asked a couple of friends who lived close to go in a bit early to get our tables. When they arrived, they told the staff why we were celebrating (5 years off chemo for my daughter). When we arrived, one of the waitresses assigned to our group explained that they had a card and some other goodies for my daughter along with a complimentary dessert. Both waitresses worked hard to keep up with our group of 20 which included 5 children under the age of 6. At the end of the meal, they brought a card that congratulated her on being cancer free and was signed by several staff members. They also gave her a "Heart of the House" hat, a bracelet and a gift card so she can come back for dinner another day. Absolutely amazing! We have always had outstanding service at Red Robin, but this was so above and beyond. I have not stopped smiling yet!! I\'d love to share the picture of my daughter in her hat if you can tell me how to do that. Thanks for being a wonderful example of excellent customer service!!!'

b'T'is the season for sharing. Your name isn't Jim or any variation (even female variations!) thereof?  Pass on that email you got and chalk it up to spreading cheer to your Jim friends this holiday season! It's one email that may not pertain directly to you, but that's okay! If you're *really* offended by that one email, click one button to delete it. I personally passed it on to those friends of mine who will be ecstatic to get something free for a fun and innovative reason like having a name that matches a brand.

Despite the use of the word "him" in reference to the name "Jim" in the email, nowhere does it state that this promotion exclude females! The official rules even state the variations of the name Jim that this offer is open to. "Offer is good for all guests named Jim and the derivative of it ~ James, Jamie, Jaime, Jaimie, Jami, Jamey, Jameson, Jimmy, Jimmi, Jimi, Jim and of course, Jimbo."  The official RR posters on this page have confirmed that. Pass the email on to any of those people, male or female, and feel good that you took part in giving something free to those awesomely named individuals this holiday season.

PS. Sorry if I offended anyone by saying it's a holiday season! I don't want the haters to lynch me for not respecting their celebratory seasons!'

b"To CEO of Red Robin Mr Stephen Carley:

I would like to know; the corporate business practice on serving 2 year olds in high chair? I was asked how many for seating, I said 2 1/2, which is three people, Myself, My Husband, and My 2 Year Old Son. I was told by Larry that corporate business practice is to seat my wife and... me on two topper booth (because they only account for the adults only), when 4 topper booths are available.

I explained that this is not right, and I have never been insulted by a manager thinking I was wrong, to identify myself, my Husband, and my son as 3 people. Why would a company accept this behavior as acceptable? Also, my son has Down\xe2\x80\x99s syndrome and I believe your company's staff has a problem with disabilities with his image. 

Your store managers do not recognize children as a person for seating and when that your staff at your company does not recognize has a disability.

Thank you for poor service."

b'Hello my name is Nick Cervantes and I am currently deployed to Southern Afghanistan in support of Operation Enduring Freedom. Recently I was on the phone with my mom and she asked me if I needed anything. At the time I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t think of a single thing, but told her I would think about it and get back to her. The next time we spoke I told her now this is going to sound a little out there, but can you send a bottle of Red Robin seasoning salt? The reason this all came up is one night when we were at work the topic was brought up about the best restaurants in the United States.'

b"A lot of good restaurants were named in this conversation but it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t till one of my Sgt's said \xe2\x80\x9c you haven\xe2\x80\x99t had a burger till you have had a Red Robin burger\xe2\x80\x9d. After that we all talked about Red Robin for a long time. Red Robin was something we all had in common. Everyone talked about their favorite burger, the amazing bottomless steak fries and the freckled lemonade. So my mom went to Red Robin in Yuba City ,CA and told them my story and they just loved the fact that I wanted RR Seasoning Salt."

b'My mom was very impressed with the manager, John Lear, and the service she received at the Yuba City store. She was so touched by the outpouring of kindness that she called Red Robin Gourmet Burgers INC in Greenwood Village, Colorado. She came in contact with a Travis Tamlin and explained my story and what had happened at the Red Robin in Yuba City CA. This inspired Travis to get his own care package together including the famous Red Robin seasoning, t-shirts, as well as a couple of Red Robin footballs in case we got bored. We had no idea that a care package was being sent to us from Red Robin. My mom had only told me that she would work on getting the seasoning salt for us as soon as possible.'

b'When we opened the care package it was like Christmas Day! There was a letter on top so I opened it and it explained everything that had happened. All of us here want to give a big thank you to Red Robin for the gifts but, the most important thing is Red Robin went the distance to bring a little piece of home to all of us. Thank you so much for everything.

Your friend,
Nick Cervantes'
b"Just hit my 5 year mark working for the company! It's a great place to work and an even better place to eat!!!"
